Join your favorite crew as we come together and celebrate a night of electronic dance music that will surely blow you away. %100 legal venue, 3 stages of earth shattering sound, vendors, live art, and talent that will inspire you. Flock has deticated its sound, time and energy to the valley with passion and a belief that az has one of the best underground scenes in america today, known for doing the simple things. DJ ENRIE (LA, 93.9 , MOONSHINE RECORDINGS) Nominated for Industry Insider's 1996 Commercial DJ of the Year, power mixer DJ Enrie turns up the heat all year round. A gifted high-powered DJ, Enrie continues to captivate the dance community with a never-ending mix of his passion for the turntables and his lust for house music. Born in Queens, New York, Enrie moved to southern California in 1988. He quickly created a foundation for himself in the industry while working at American Trax Record Pool and working the clubland scene throughout Los Angeles. Befriending two DJs, Richard "Humpty" Vission and Tony B. who had mixshows on L.A.'s Power 106 FM proved to be most beneficial for Enrie's budding career. As their stars rose, Vission and Tony B. were required to travel quite regularly. They soon enlisted Enrie's mixing talents to fill in while they were out of town. With his rising noteriety as a house savvy innovator Enrie was also collaborating with Vission on the "Power Tools" show. Enrie subsequently proved his talents were far more worthy of a regular position at the station and his signature mid-day mix show "Power Workout" was born. The success of the two "Power" shows helped Enrie give underground house music a broad-based audience. His signature "Power Workout" was the springboard to the rising influence of House music in Los Angeles. It was this versatility that earned him remixing work with Amber, Frankie Cutlass and Nina Lares. Enrie took advantage of the latest of musical trends by successfully releasing a series of mix CD's on labels such as PR Records, Priority and Underground Construction. In 1988, after creating a new studio for himself, Enrie released his most hi-tech mix compilation, "Inside My Mind," on Main Source Records. This double packet featured an interactive multi-media CD which included his music video, background information, games, tour dates, a special interview as well a virtual mixer, allowing fans be the "DJ." Enrie has found a home for his House at Moonshine Music. His 1999 debut release "Turn It Up" featured 17 tracks of cutting edge hard house with a relentless tempo. Mid-Summer 2000 was prime time for "Turn It Up 2", a compilation reflecting the hard bangin', body movin' house Enrie had been throwing down in the clubs. "Keeping it real and staying true to my fans is what it's all about", says Enrie. On his latest effort, "Welcome to the Mix Show, " Enrie showcases his hard-bangin', body-movin' House selections as well as his newest single, "Gimme Funk," which Moonshine Music will release on vinyl as part of an artist deal. From his humble beginnings at American Trax, Enrie worked his way up to "Power Tools," on to his signature "Power Workout" show, all the while building a loyal audience of devoted fans. CLOUDSKIPPER (CM Beatz / Raw Elements / KFA / OmniEra Entertainment) From his start as a DJ nearly a decade ago, Cloudskipper has been a leader in the North American hardcore music scene. His rise to become one of the most popular and anticipated hardcore djs and producers is especially prevalent in his live sets, taking you on a journey through the various sub-genres he manipulates. Having toured all over the world in almost every major city in the US, Canada, and England, with several releases on labels such as Raw Elements, KFA, Supernova, and Bedlam, it's no wonder Cloudskipper continues to take hardcore and its audience by storm! JAYVON AND MC XYZ (SUGAR CODED RECS, OUTLOOK SKATEBOARDS, LA)

There is definitely something about Jayvon. From the moment the LA based DJ started handing out mix CDs at underground raves he was destined for success. In just a few short years, he has gone from relative obscurity to playing alongside DJ Craze and making an appearance at the Winter Music Conference..s ultra-exclusive World of Drum and Bass party. His success is a no brainer really since Jayvon is blessed with impeccable turntable skills, boundless energy, poster boy good looks and a humble demeanor. With a slew of mix CDs to his name, J is poised to take the drum and bass community by storm. With the release of his brand new mix compilation Electric he again steps up his game dropping a mix of eclectic tracks guaranteed to rock any dancefloor. Urban Breakbeat was so impressed by ..Electric.. that we knew Jayvon had to be on our site. We were able to catch up with him to discuss his past, present and bright future. This is the new generation of American drum and bass, so get ready! LADIES FREE TILL 930pm 930-10pm just $5 bux for the females Main Stage - Four to the floor

Live Rattlesnakes Released In 'Snakes On A Plane' Theater Two live diamondback rattlesnakes were released in an Arizona movie theater during a showing of the new film "Snakes on a Plane," according to Local 6 News. Authorities said pranksters released the young venomous rattlesnakes in a dark theater at the AMC Desert Ridge near Tatum and Loop 101 in Phoenix. The two snakes caused a panic in the dark theater, according to the report. "That to me is very scary," herpetological association representative Tom Whiting said. "I would hate to be watching a movie about snakes and have a rattlesnake bite me." Wranglers were called to collect the snakes, the report said. No one was injured in the incident and, so far, the culprits have not been caught.Officials believe the snakes were smuggled into the theater in backpacks. "This thing is under someone's chair and they go to sit and they just push your foot in the air and startle it -- obviously all they got to do is startle this thing," Phoenix Herpetological Society spokesman Daniel Marchand said. "It's dark. They can't see you, you know that well. If it's scared, boom it strikes." The snakes were released into the desert.
